.TH QVM-MANAGER 1 "January 2025" "v1.0.3" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
qvm-manager \- QEMU Virtual Machine Manager
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B qvm-manager
[OPTION]
.br
.B qvm-manager
[VERSION] [VALUE]
.SH DESCRIPTION
qvm-manager is a command line interface (CLI) tool for managing QEMU virtual machines. It is an extremely simple and lightweight but powerful QEMU hypervisor designed to get the best performance from your host machine. QVM works in conjunction with Kernel-based Virtual Machine (KVM) to provide hardware-assisted virtualization, enhancing performance by allowing virtual machines to run at near-native speeds. QVM also provides users with a user-friendly graphical user interface (GUI) for a smoother virtualization experience.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-list-vm
List all existing VMs.
.TP
.B \-\-start <vm_name>
Start an existing VM.
.TP
.B \-\-show-v <vm_name>
Show a VM's Specs.
.TP
.B \-\-list-iso
List all local ISO images.
.TP
.B \-\-gui
Launch the QVM graphical user interface.
.TP
.B \-\-delete-vm <vm_name>
Delete a specified VM.
.TP
.B \-\-delete-iso <iso_name|all>
Delete a specified ISO image or all ISO images.
.TP
.B \-\-pull-iso <image_name>
Download a specified ISO image.
.TP
.B \-\-snap <vm_name> \-\-tag <snapshot_name>
Save a snapshot of an existing VM.
.TP
.B \-\-revert <vm_name> \-\-tag <snapshot_name>
Use a snapshot to revert the VM back to a previous state.
.TP
.B \-\-delete-snap <vm_name> \-\-tag <snapshot_name>
Delete a specified snapshot.
.TP
.B \-\-help, \-h
Display this help message.
.TP
.B \-\-version, \-v [VALUE]
Display version information of QVM installation.
.RS
.TP
.B \-ac
Version data for QVM & its components.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B qvm-manager \-\-start myvm
Start the VM named "myvm".
.TP
.B qvm-manager \-\-list-vm
List all existing virtual machines.
.TP
.B qvm-manager \-\-pull-iso ubuntu-noble
Download the Ubuntu 20.04 Noble ISO image.
.TP
.B qvm-manager \-\-snap myvm \-\-tag backup1
Create a snapshot of "myvm" with the tag "backup1".
.SH GUI TIPS AND HINTS
.IP $$bu 2
VM templating can only be implemented via the GUI.
.IP $$bu 2
VMs can only be renamed via the GUI.
.IP $$bu 2
Most GUI messages are automatically sent to the CLI, providing a useful log of the current session's activities.
.IP $$bu 2
It is generally much easier to manage VMs via the GUI. However, using the CLI can be a more efficient way of completing certain tasks.
